# Product in std::iter - Rust

## Trait [std](../index.html)::[iter](index.html)::[Product](#)

1.12.0 · [source](https://doc.rust-lang.org/1.80.0/src/core/iter/traits/accum.rs.html#38) ·

```
pub trait Product<A = Self>: Sized {
    // Required method
    fn product<I>(iter: I) -> Self
       where I: Iterator<Item = A>;
}
```

Expand description

Trait to represent types that can be created by multiplying elements of an iterator.

This trait is used to implement [`Iterator::product()`](about:blank/trait.Iterator.html#method.product "method std::iter::Iterator::product"). Types which implement this trait can be generated by using the [`product()`](about:blank/trait.Iterator.html#method.product "method std::iter::Iterator::product") method on an iterator. Like [`FromIterator`](trait.FromIterator.html "trait std::iter::FromIterator"), this trait should rarely be called directly.

1.12.0 · [source](https://doc.rust-lang.org/1.80.0/src/core/iter/traits/accum.rs.html#42)

Method which takes an iterator and generates `Self` from the elements by multiplying the items.

Trait std::iter::Product

1.12.0 · source · 
pub trait Product<A = Self>: Sized {
    // Required method
    fn product<I>(iter: I) -> Self
       where I: Iterator<Item = A>;
}
Expand description

Trait to represent types that can be created by multiplying elements of an iterator.

This trait is used to implement Iterator::product(). Types which implement this trait can be generated by using the product() method on an iterator. Like FromIterator, this trait should rarely be called directly.

Required Methods§

1.12.0 · source

fn product<I>(iter: I) -> Self
where I: Iterator<Item = A>,

Method which takes an iterator and generates Self from the elements by multiplying the items.
